    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-10-18T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-10-18T08:00:00-05:00" n="79"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d79">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">780.5/10–1851: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Egypt</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_CJ1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-10-18T15:00:00+02:00"
                            >October 18, 1951—3 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>511. When note<note n="1" xml:id="d79fn1">Contained in telegram 584 to Cairo,
                        October 16, <ref target="#pg_226">p. 226</ref>.</note> was delivered (<gloss
                        target="#t_remytel1">remytel</gloss> 506, October 17)<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d79fn2">Not printed, but summarized in footnote 3, <ref
                            target="#pg_227">p. 227</ref>.</note> Under Secretary Ministry Foreign
                    Affairs, who is ordinarily a reasoned individual, spent half hour tearing <gloss
                        target="#t_MEC1">MEC</gloss> proposals apart.</p>
                <p>I must remind Dept that our Ambassadors expected this type of reaction, and it
                    was for this reason that we so earnestly recommended that proposals not be put
                    forward at this time (<gloss target="#t_mytel1">mytel</gloss> 447, October
                        10).<note n="3" xml:id="d79fn3">Not printed, but see editorial note, <ref
                            target="#pg_205">p. 205</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Having torn them to pieces, we cannot hope that Egyptians will give any further
                    consideration to proposals as they now stand. If we are to take advantage of
                    crack in door <gloss target="#t_remytel1">remytel</gloss> 506 we will have to
                    come up with proposals which at least will have to be reworded. We must realize
                    that Egyptians can only think of the problem in <pb facs="0271" n="231"
                        xml:id="pg_231"/> terms of past history, and cannot see the realities of the
                    present World situation. We must not expect them to consider the problem
                    logically. Sent Dept 511, rptd info London 209, Paris 89, Ankara 71.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
